	<text>
		<body>

			<p>Doc 8</p>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-542" type="subject">precautions</term> taken against
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3144096/kingdom-of-norway.html">Norway</placeName>, from the beginning, were directed mainly towards
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-583" type="subject">Full Jews</term>. Full Jews are understood as
				persons whose parents were both of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewish</term>
				descent and persons belonging to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Mosaic Faith
					Society</term>. On the other hand, all such persons were also subject to the precautions taken and it did not play any role,
				whether he was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject">married</term> to a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">non-Jew</term> or in a marriage to a non-Jew with
				children. Exceptions to this rule were probably, both so that some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374"
					type="subject">Half-Jews</term> may have been <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject"
					>deported</term>, and so that <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject"
				>Full-Jews</term>who have been married to non-Jews have been allowed to stay in the country. Thus, in three <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">Concentration Camps</term> in Norway, there are
				various <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term>, all of whom are full Jews. Of
				these camps, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3134331/tonsberg.html">Tønsberg</placeName> with approx. 50 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">interned</term> was the largest. Interned half-Jews
				are found in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-952" type="camp">Grini</placeName>, but these are not
				interned because of their descent, but because charges of some kind have been raised against them.</p>
			<p><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> who are Norwegian citizens have been
				interned on the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-594" type="subject">request</term> of the Germans, but
				on the other side, the Germans have agreed that no more <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-575"
					type="subject">deportation</term> will take place from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3144096/kingdom-of-norway.html"
					>Norway</placeName> of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> who are
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3144096/kingdom-of-norway.html">Norwegian</placeName> citizens. Furthermore, the German
				authorities have agreed to disregard wealth <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-584" type="subject"
					>confiscation</term> in cases where a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject"
					>Jewish</term> man is detained in a concentration camp or deported, and a non-<term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewish</term> wife must now seek self-employment.</p>
			<p>Furthermore, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> over the age of 65 are set
				free.</p>
			<p><date when="1943-10-25">October 25 1943</date>.</p>
